 = 6\n| AP_7            = 1 <small>(45)</small>\n| coaches_7       = 1 <small>(26)</small>\n| AP_8            = 1 <small>(43)</small>\n| coaches_8       = 1 <small>(36)</small>\n| AP_9            = 1 <small>(46)</small>\n| coaches_9       = 1 <small>(41)</small>\n| cfp_9           = 1\n| AP_10           = 1 <small>(45)</small>\n| coaches_10      = 1 <small>(40)</small>\n| cfp_10          = 1\n| AP_11           = 1 <small>(48)</small>\n| coaches_11      = 1 <small>(41)</small>\n| cfp_11          = 1\n| AP_12           = 4\n| coaches_12      = 4\n| cfp_12          = 4\n| AP_13           = 4\n| coaches_13      = 4\n| cfp_13          = 4\n| AP_14           = 10\n| coaches_14      = 10\n| cfp_14          = 10\n| AP_15           = 8\n| coaches_15      = 8\n| cfp_15          = 7\n| AP_16           = 11\n| coaches_16      =12\n}}\n\nFollowing MSU's win over Auburn, the team was ranked Number 1 in the AP Poll for the first time in the program's history. That also marked \"the fastest [rise to the top] in AP Top 25 history.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Mississippi State Completes Fastest Ascent to No. 1 in AP Top 25 History|first=Eric|last=Vander Voort|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/poll-position/2014-10-12/mississippi-state-completes-fastest-ascent-no-1-ap-top-25|publisher=National Collegiate Athletic Association|date=October 12, 2014|accessdate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> The previous mark was six weeks by [[1954 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State in 1954]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mississippi State No. 1 in AP poll|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/11688921/mississippi-state-bulldogs-rise-no-1-associated-press-college-football-poll|work=[[ESPN]]|date=October 12, 2014|accessdate=November 18, 2014}}</ref>  The Bulldogs also became the first ever team to be ranked number 1 in the newly created College Football Playoff Poll when the initial poll was released on October 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mississippi State Leads College Football Playoff Committee\u2019s First Rankings|first=Marc|last=Tracy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/29/sports/ncaafootball/mississippi-state-leads-college-football-playoff-committees-first-rankings.html?_r=0|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 28, 2014|accessdate=October 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Mississippi State Bulldogs football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2014 Mississippi State Bulldogs Football Team}}\n[[Category:Mississippi State Bulldogs football seasons]]\n[[Category:2014 Southeastern Conference football season|Mississippi State]]\n[[Category:2014 in sports in Mississippi|Mississippi State Bulldogs f]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=2014\n  |team=Mississippi State Bulldogs\n  |sport=football\n  |image=Mississippi State Bulldogs logo.svg\n  |image_size=150px\n  |conference=Southeastern Conference\n  |short_conf=SEC\n  |division=Western Division\n  |CoachRank= 12\n  |APRank= 11\n  |CFPRank=\n  |record=10\u20133\n  |conf_record=6\u20132\n  |head_coach=[[Dan Mullen]]\n  |hc_year=6th\n  |cooff_coach1 = [[Billy Gonzales]]\n  |cooc1_year = 1st as co-OC, 2nd overall\n  |cooff_coach2 = [[John Hevesy]]\n  |cooc2_year = 1st as co-OC, 6th overall\n  |off_scheme=[[Spread option offense|Spread option]]\n  |def_coach=[[Geoff Collins (American football)|Geoff Collins]]\n  |dc_year= 4th \n  |def_scheme=[[4\u20133 defense|4\u20133]]\n  |stadium=[[Davis Wade Stadium]] (Capacity: 61,337)\n  |champion=\n  |bowl=[[2014 Orange Bowl (December)|Orange Bowl]]\n  |bowl_result= L 34\u201349 vs. [[2014 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]]\n}}\n{{2014 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''2014 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team''' represented [[Mississippi State University]] in the [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The team was coached by [[Dan Mullen]], who was in his sixth season with Mississippi State. The Bulldogs played their home games at the newly expanded and renovated [[Davis Wade Stadium]] in [[Starkville, Mississippi]] and competed in the Western Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC).\n\nThe 2014 season was one of the most successful seasons in Mississippi State's 110-year football history. In mid-October, they shot to #1 in the polls for the first time in school history, and the highest that any FBS team in Mississippi had been ranked at that late date in the season in half a century.  They ultimately finished 10\u20133, the second 10-win regular season in school history. They netted a berth in the [[2014 Orange Bowl (December)|Orange Bowl]], the second major-bowl appearance in school history, where they were defeated by [[2014 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]].\n\n==Before the season==\n\n===Previous season===\nThe [[2013 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team]] finished 7\u20136, defeating [[2013 Rice Owls football team|Rice]] in the [[2013 Liberty Bowl|Liberty Bowl]]. The Bulldogs' conference victories included a narrow win over [[2013 Kentucky Wildcats football team|Kentucky]], an overtime road win at [[2013 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]], and an overtime thriller over rival [[2013 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]] in the [[Egg Bowl]].\n\nIt was the Bulldogs' fourth straight bowl season, the first time in school history a team had accomplished this feat. The 2013 Bulldogs averaged 434 yards per game on offensive, the highest output in school history.\n\n===Departing players===\n\nKey losses for the Bulldogs included:\n*[[Denico Autry]], starting defensive end and current member of the [[Indianapolis Colts]]\n*[[Gabe Jackson]], offensive guard who was selected by the Raiders in the third round of the [[2014 NFL Draft]]\n*[[LaDarius Perkins]], starting running back and fifth on the Bulldogs' [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football statistical leaders#Rushing|career leaderboard]] with 2,554 rushing yards\n*[[Tyler Russell]], whose 5,441 passing yards ranked third in [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football statistical leaders#Passing|school history]] at the time\n*[[Deontae Skinner]], starting linebacker and current member of the [[New York Giants]]\n*Nickoe Whitley, a four-year starter at safety with 15 career interceptions and 2 key late-game forced fumbles to seal games in 2013\n\n===Preseason prognostication===\nThe Bulldogs were picked to finish 5th in the SEC West by a vote of 229 media writers at the 2014 SEC Media Days,<ref>{{cite web |title=SEC preseason media poll picks Alabama over Auburn to win league title|date = July 17, 2014|first = Michael |last = Casagrande|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/07/sec_preseason_media_poll_picks.html|publisher=AL.com|accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> while Athlon Sports<ref>{{cite web |title=Early SEC Football Predictions for 2014|date = January 16, 2014|first = Steven |last = Lassan| url= http://athlonsports.com/college-football/early-sec-football-predictions-2014|publisher=Athlon|accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> and NBC Sports<ref>{{cite web |title=CFT 2014 Preseason Preview: SEC Predictions|date = August 18, 2014|first = John |last = Taylor| url= http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2014/08/18/cft-2014-preseason-preview-sec-predictions/|publisher=Athlon|accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> both picked the Bulldogs to come in sixth.\n\n===Roster and staff===\n{{American football roster/Header|year=2014|team=Mississippi State Bulldogs|teamcolors=y\n|offensive_players=\n{{American football roster/Player|first=De'Runnya|last=Wilson|num=1|pos=WR|class=So|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|first=Jameon|last=Lewis|num=4|pos=WR|class=Sr|link=y}}\n{{American football roster/Player|first=Fred|last=Brown|num=5|pos=WR|class=So|link=}}\n{{American football roster/Player|first=Malcolm|last=Johnson|num=6|pos=TE|class=Sr|link=y|dab=Malcolm Johnson (tight end)}}\n{{American football roster/Player|first=Nick|last=Griffin|num=7|pos